Youth, know it to be thus!” Śikṣ places
                the last two lines of verse 8 after verse 16, which also refers to the giving of
                Dharma. {8}

Manifests by having an attitude of equality toward all beings.” The last two lines of this verse read differently in
                Taishō 310: “Through having an attitude of equality toward all beings, one has the
                form that delights beings upon seeing” (等心於眾生，觀者無厭足). {10}

When one abandons senseless talk.” The
                fourth line of this verse in Taishō 310 reads, “when one respects all beings”
                  (敬重於眾生). {12}

By becoming familiar with emptiness.”
                Here the Sanskrit applies the adverb “always” to “becoming familiar,” which are both
                in the same pāda in the Sanskrit manuscript: śūnyatāṃ bhāvayen nityam. {18}

With their diverse inclinations?” The
                last two lines of this verse in Taishō 310 read, “How does one make beings / feel
                delighted upon seeing them?” (云何令世間，見者皆歡喜). {21}

How do they obtain miraculous powers?”
                In Taishō 310 the order of these lines is different: miraculous powers come first,
                followed by previous lives and then defilements. {29}

So that even ten million māras can do no harm?” Given the omission of the first line in Taishō 310 of
                this verse, the fourth line differs as well: “Hopefully the Honored One will explain
                it” (唯願人尊說). {39}
